{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487499"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:12:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:12:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"360"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/360"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.13,0.12,0.56,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"360"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103679"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/360"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"360"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86096"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4492"},{"type":"tags","id":"8116"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35568"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103679"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 88-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing upper abdominal pain and shortness of breath. Her medical history includes hypertension and coronary artery stenting after a myocardial infarction 10 years ago. She has a 30 pack-year smoking history but ceased about 20 years ago. Her medications include perindopril, simvastatin and aspirin. On examination, she appears comfortable. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 136/84 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. On auscultation there are some crackles at both lung bases, but otherwise her chest is clear. The rest of physical examination is unremarkable. A CT scan is performed. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the bronchus","Congestive cardiac failure","Abdominal aortic aneurysm","Para-oesophageal hernia","Cavitating lung lesion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA large cavity can be seen between the heart and the aorta on CT imaging. It contains material of varying density (food) and air (Image). It lies alongside the oesophagus where air is visible in the lumen. This radiological appearance is characteristic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Epara-oesophageal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the bronchus\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears as a solid mass lesion, often with associated lymphadenopathy or pleural effusion, which are not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongestive cardiac failure\u003C/strong\u003E would show features of pulmonary oedema including interstitial thickening, pleural effusions, and enlarged cardiac silhouette on imaging, none of which are present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal aortic aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a dilated aorta with a diameter greater than 3cm, which is not seen on this scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECavitating lung lesion\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as an air-filled space within the lung parenchyma, often with an irregular wall, rather than the retrocardiac location seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost hiatus hernias are asymptomatic. When symptoms do occur, they typically include gastro-oesophageal reflux and heartburn. More severe symptoms could include nausea and vomiting. A very large para-oesophageal hernia could have compressive effects on surrounding structures and cause chest pain, upper abdominal pain or shortness of breath. In this case, the para-oesophageal hernia is likely an incidental finding and unrelated to her present symptoms. Her shortness of breath is more likely related to her smoking history and possible cardiac disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Para-oesophageal hernias are most often asymptomatic and in general, do not present with respiratory symptoms.","Para-oesophageal hernias appear as retrocardiac masses containing air and food debris on CT imaging."],"references":["Roman S, Kahrilas PJ. The diagnosis and management of hiatus hernia. BMJ 2014; 349:g6154. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25341679/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86096"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"360"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20013"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21915"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20013"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/700ba188-d39f-4645-a492-3560167bfd44.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/700ba188-d39f-4645-a492-3560167bfd44.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":531,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"21915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21915"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/crIhM9tq5Z0wk9TQK4bSUmCXBXPaQq.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/crIhM9tq5Z0wk9TQK4bSUmCXBXPaQq.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":531,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/item